      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are absolutely right; the nearest neighbor method is a classic \"greedy\" algorithm that often leads to suboptimal results, especially when it forces you to travel a long distance to close the loop at the end. A better approach for small loops like yours is the \"2-opt\" heuristic, which looks at the entire sequence and tries to swap two stops to see if the total distance decreases.\n\nImagine your route as a line of 12 points; you would randomly pick two non-adjacent points, swap their positions, and calculate if the new path is shorter. You would repeat this swap process over and over, keeping only the changes that save gas, until no single swap improves the route. This forces the algorithm to consider the global geometry rather than just the immediate next step, effectively smoothing out the \"bad spots\" at the end.\n\nSince you don't have specialized software, you can simulate this mentally or on paper by sketching a few different permutations of your 12 stops and visually comparing the total length of the loops, looking for patterns where you can \"cut out\" a large detour by swapping two middle stops. It requires more effort than the greedy method, but it guarantees a much more efficient path by",
